<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="329" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,153,1583]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1160,1187]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Villamizar &amp; Fernández &amp; Vivallo, 2020" authorityName="Villamizar &amp; Fernández &amp; Vivallo" authorityYear="2020" box="[342,543,1161,1187]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Xylocopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="romeroi" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[342,543,1161,1187]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Xylocopa romeroi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[551,614,1161,1187]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[551,614,1161,1187]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is one of the largest species of the subgenus that have the base of labrum with three tubercles of similar length and not a single, large, capitate tuberculum as can be found in other large species as 
<taxonomicName authority="Villamizar &amp; Fernández &amp; Vivallo, 2020" authorityName="Villamizar &amp; Fernández &amp; Vivallo" authorityYear="2020" box="[232,386,1234,1259]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Xylocopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="auriventris" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[232,386,1234,1259]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">X. auriventris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[393,456,1233,1259]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[393,456,1233,1259]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1809" box="[470,608,1233,1259]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Xylocopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dimidiata">
<emphasis box="[470,608,1233,1259]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">X. dimidiata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Smith" authorityYear="1874" box="[623,758,1233,1259]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Xylocopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="metallica">
<emphasis box="[623,758,1233,1259]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">X. metallica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Smith" authorityYear="1854" box="[812,947,1233,1259]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Xylocopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simillima">
<emphasis box="[812,947,1233,1259]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">X. simillima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,153,1583]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
This new species was collected approximately 100 years ago, remaining unstudied until now. A Colombian female from the department of 
<collectingRegion box="[501,571,1305,1331]" country="Colombia" name="Cauca" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Cauca</collectingRegion>
contained in MNCN was identified by 
<bibRefCitation author="Dusmet-Alonso, J. M." box="[1015,1274,1305,1331]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" pagination="5 - 58" refId="ref30424" refString="Dusmet-Alonso, J. M. (1924) Las &quot; Xylocopa &quot; (Hymen. Apidae) en las colecciones de Madrid. Trabajos del Museo Nacional de Ciencias Naturales de Madrid, Serie Zoologica, 49, 5 - 58." type="journal article" year="1924">Dusmet-Alonso (1924)</bibRefCitation>
as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Say" authorityYear="1837" box="[1312,1436,1305,1331]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Xylocopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lateralis">
<emphasis box="[1312,1436,1305,1331]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">X. lateralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the association by similarity with a Mexican male. We examined that specimen and it corresponds to a female of 
<taxonomicName authority="Villamizar &amp; Fernández &amp; Vivallo, 2020" authorityName="Villamizar &amp; Fernández &amp; Vivallo" authorityYear="2020" box="[182,303,1378,1403]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Xylocopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="romeroi" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[182,303,1378,1403]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">X. romeroi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[311,374,1377,1403]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[311,374,1377,1403]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
Curiously, Dusmet-Alonso (op. cit.) mentioned that the exemplar has strong violaceous highlights and only refers to the whitish hairs on lateral sides of last terga. The Mexican male was also examined and we think that it fits into the concept of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Maidl" authorityYear="1912" box="[544,698,1450,1475]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Xylocopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caviventris">
<emphasis box="[544,698,1450,1475]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">X. caviventris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
than 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Say" authorityYear="1837" box="[760,883,1449,1475]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Xylocopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lateralis">
<emphasis box="[760,883,1449,1475]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">X. lateralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, its real identity can be solved with the study of more exemplars of that region.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,153,1583]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
The 
<typeStatus box="[250,348,1521,1547]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">holotype</typeStatus>
and 
<typeStatus box="[404,500,1521,1547]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">paratype</typeStatus>
were collected in the Pacific region (Pacific domain 
<emphasis box="[1099,1161,1522,1547]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">sensu</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Morrone, J. J." box="[1169,1339,1521,1547]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" pagination="1 - 110" refId="ref32894" refString="Morrone, J. J. (2014) Biogeographical regionalisation of the Neotropical region. Zootaxa, 3782, 1 - 110. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3782.1.1" type="journal article" year="2014">Morrone, 2014</bibRefCitation>
) and the male is unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
